        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2020-09-09 19:13:26.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\n> Patch Set 4:\n> \n> (2 comments)\n\nThanks for the clarification. But I still have a question: how to know if a node is (or is not) top-level? \"tunnel-xconnect\", for example, is a child under \"allotted-resource\". How can we tell \"tunnel-xconnect\" is not a top-level?",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "5fb294c309e2d8e1d6c5dc00e17c3507118a04fa",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 75,
          "name": "Venkata Harish Kajur",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "vk250x@att.com",
          "username": "vk250x"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2020-09-09 20:03:54.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\n> Patch Set 4:\n> \n> > Patch Set 4:\n> > \n> > (2 comments)\n> \n> Thanks for the clarification. But I still have a question: how to know if a node is (or is not) top-level? \"tunnel-xconnect\", for example, is a child under \"allotted-resource\". How can we tell \"tunnel-xconnect\" is not a top-level?\n\nAny object that is under the namespace.\n\nExample:\n\n 632         <java-type name=\"CloudInfrastructure\">\n 633             <xml-properties>\n 634                 <xml-property name=\"description\" value=\"Namespace for cloud infrastructure.\"/>\n 635             </xml-properties>\n 636             <xml-root-element name=\"cloud-infrastructure\"/>\n 637             <java-attributes>\n 638                 <xml-element java-attribute=\"complexes\" name=\"complexes\" type=\"inventory.aai.onap.org.v21.Complexes\"/>\n 639                 <xml-element java-attribute=\"cloudRegions\" name=\"cloud-regions\" type=\"inventory.aai.onap.org.v21.CloudRegions\"/>\n 640                 <xml-element java-attribute=\"networkProfiles\" name=\"network-profiles\" type=\"inventory.aai.onap.org.v21.NetworkProfiles\"/>\n 641                 <xml-element java-attribute=\"pservers\" name=\"pservers\" type=\"inventory.aai.onap.org.v21.Pservers\"/>\n 642                 <xml-element java-attribute=\"virtualDataCenters\" name=\"virtual-data-centers\" type=\"inventory.aai.onap.org.v21.VirtualDataCenters\"/>\n 643                 <xml-element java-attribute=\"operationalEnvironments\" name=\"operational-environments\" type=\"inventory.aai.onap.org.v21.OperationalEnvironments\"/>\n 644                 <xml-element java-attribute=\"geoRegions\" name=\"geo-regions\" type=\"inventory.aai.onap.org.v21.GeoRegions\"/>\n 645                 <xml-element java-attribute=\"networkTechnologies\" name=\"network-technologies\" type=\"inventory.aai.onap.org.v21.NetworkTechnologies\"/>\n 646             </java-attributes>\n 647         </java-type>\n\n\nComplex, Cloud-Region, Pserver, NetworkProfile, VirtualDataCenter, OperationalEnvironment,GeoRegions, NetworkTechnology are all top level objects because they are in the namespace CloudInfrastructure.\n\nThere are other namespaces in the project called Network, Business, Common, ServiceDesignAndCreation and ExternalSystem and if they are under there then its definitely top level object",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
